 1. Mount Namespace
4
Definition

A Mount Namespace isolates the filesystem mount points for a process or container.

This means each container can have its own view of the filesystem even though it runs on the same host OS.

Key Idea

Processes inside a container cannot see mount points created outside their namespace unless they are shared.

Example

Suppose on the host:

/home
/data
/mnt/backup

Inside a Docker container:

/        (container root filesystem)
/app
/tmp

The container cannot see /mnt/backup unless it is explicitly mounted.

Example Docker command:

docker run -v /host/data:/container/data ubuntu

Here:

Host: /host/data
Container: /container/data

The mount namespace allows Docker to attach host directories inside the container safely.

Why it is useful

Containers have isolated filesystems

Prevents processes from accessing host files

Allows volume mounting

2. UTS Namespace
4
Definition

UTS Namespace isolates system identifiers such as:

Hostname

NIS domain name

UTS stands for:

Unix Time Sharing System

Key Idea

Each container can have its own hostname independent of the host system.

Example

Host machine hostname:

host-machine

Run container:

docker run -it ubuntu bash

Inside container:

hostname

Output might be:

3f9c12ab45

Docker automatically assigns a unique container hostname.

You can also set it manually:

docker run --hostname mycontainer ubuntu

Inside container:

hostname
mycontainer
Why it is useful

Containers can have different hostnames

Useful for microservices and networking

Prevents conflicts with host system identity

Quick Comparison
Feature	Mount Namespace	UTS Namespace
Controls	Filesystem mount points	Hostname & domain
Purpose	Filesystem isolation	System identity isolation
Example	/app, /data mounts	hostname command
Used for	Volumes & container FS	Container naming